P.Span: Select additional data filters to examine data by type of bias motivation, victim demographic characteristics, and offense type.
Identifying and recording hate crimes known to law enforcement in the Uniform Crime Reporting Program

The FBI’s Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) Program collects crime incident data submitted by law enforcement agencies through the National Incident-Based Reporting System (NIBRS). Participating agencies also submit information about the number of incidents and victimizations of hate crime that were motivated, in whole or in part, by the offender’s bias against a victim’s race or ethnicity, religion, disability, sexual orientation, gender, or gender identity. Law enforcement is advised that the mere fact of an offender’s bias against a victim does not mean that a hate crime was involved. The law enforcement agency must determine that sufficient evidence exists to lead a reasonable person to ascertain that the offender’s criminal act must have been motivated, in whole or in part, by his or her bias.

Incidents known to law enforcement and suspected of being hate crimes are subject to a two-tier review process. The purpose of the two-tier procedure is to ensure that suspected bias-motivated incidents undergo two levels of review within the reporting agency. First, the officer who responds to the incident must determine if there is any indication that the offender was motivated by bias. The responding officer must designate the incident as a “suspected bias-motivated crime” and send it for secondary review by an officer or unit of the agency that is trained in or has greater expertise in hate crime matters. This latter officer or unit has the responsibility for making the final decision as to whether the incident will be categorized as a hate crime. Only after the incident has undergone the second review and is determined to be hate crime can that hate crime incident be reported to the HCSP.
Law enforcement agency participation in reporting hate crime to the UCR
Training and guidance for law enforcement on hate crime reporting in the UCR

The FBI instructs law enforcement agencies on how to properly record hate crimes, for the purposes of uniform reporting to the HCSP. The program uses a set of standardized definitions of the categories and types of bias motivation, to ensure that each participating agency applies the same set of criteria for classifying bias.
UCR hate crime data reflect reported incidents and victims rather than estimates

The UCR publishes data on law enforcement reports of criminal offenses determined to be motivated by bias. The data reflect the number of incidents, offenses, victims, and known offenders submitted by participating agencies. The data are not weighted to represent nonreporting agencies and are not subject to any imputation or statistical estimation procedures. Therefore, no standard errors have been produced to evaluate the quality of or variability in the reported data.
